ğŸ“Œ `echo`
--------------------------------------------

**File**: `builtin_echo.c`  
**Behavior**:
- [â] Prints arguments to `stdout`, separated by spaces, followed by a newline. - [â] It writes all the non-flag tokens to the standard input in order, separated by spaces, followed by a linebreak (\n)
- [â] If the `-n` option is given, suppresses the newline.
- [â] Handle multiple `-n` (like `echo -n -n hi` should suppress newline).
- [â“] Should be interruptible by `Ctrl+C` before execution starts.

**Example**:
INPUT                                   SHELL
> echo hello world                      echo hello world
> echo -n hello world                   hello world.%
> echo -nnnn asdasdasd                  asdasdasd%
> echo -n -n asdasdasd                  asdasdasd%
> echo -n           asdasdasd           asdasdasd%
> echo asdasdasdasd -n                  asdasdasdasd -n
> echo -nnnnn -nnnnnnnn asdasdasd       asdasdasd% 

ğŸ’¡ Should you replicate that % in your minishell?
No, you shouldn't print % manually.
	ğŸŸ  Instead, your minishell should:
	ğŸ”¸ respect the -n flag (i.e., not print \n)
	ğŸ”¸ wait for and display the prompt correctly after command execution
	ğŸŸ  The % will appear naturally if:
	ğŸ”¸ the previous command didnâ€™t print a newline
	ğŸ”¸ your shell uses % as the PS1 prompt character (common in zsh)

